## Cardigan’s Iron Shirt

> Troi mae'r Olwyn uwch lys y byd;
> Aeth y tywysogion i'w pridd tawel;
> Erys yr hen fryniau'n cofio.

> The Wheel turns above the court of the world;
> The princes have gone to their quiet earth;
> The old hills remain remembering.

It was indeed quiet above the swirling tides of the Swellies today. A typical shower had come down earlier that morning but it was nothing compared to the winter squalls that would arrive in the next few months. A few ships carrying local copper, iron, and lead were set to take advantage of this and set sail for Bruges and Paris that evening. In exchange, they would bring back ever in demand Saltpeter for the region’s ‘sour’ soil and continental spirits to help the labourers forget their troubles at the end of the day. And that was really all that mattered, everyone just had to keep working.

Michel de Joinville, Baron of Cardigan, was not a fool in this. Most would likely simply label him economical or avaricious depending on viewpoint, and behind closed doors. His work in improving the output of Northern Wales’s mines and farms earned him a **midas touched** reputation in London and a **stubborn** one closer to his family's estates just south of Aberystwyth. Though he was despised by many locals in Gwynedd this success now secured his position as **Justiciar of Wales** - the King’s chief minister in the directly ruled shires of North and South Wales.

The closest Wales has to a ‘capital’ is [Caernarfon Castle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caernarfon_Castle), located in the northern lowlands just opposite Anglesey. From here English rule is literally built in stone in conjunction with the rest of the [Ring of Iron](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_of_Iron). The entire system stands in defense of the [Statute of Rhuddlan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statute_of_Rhuddlan) and 102 year English reign over all of Wales <@1106651545296195655>.

-# *Caernarfon Castle and the Menai Strait*

Cambro-Norman, English, and variously French lords have ruled and lived in large parts of Wales for 305 years by now. Their actions may be remarked as “gratuitous cruelty” by many local Cambrians but their long-lasting influence is proof of its apparent efficacy. Their stone-built Castles rise above the rooftops of Wales, [with little interruption](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madog_ap_Llywelyn), nearly as steadfastly as the very hills themselves.

**A fo ben, bid bont.**
